\begin_layout Section
Tracking Methods 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerous algorithms can be used for tracking in a wireless mesh network.
 All algorithms can be categorized into three general methods of tracking.
 These are proximity method, scene analysis method and triangulation method
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proximity method uses sensor or nodes that would be able to identify a target
 near its vicinity or area 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

.
 Sensors would look for signals sent by a target using transceivers or RFID
 tags.
 Usually a lot of nodes are positioned in different sections to cover the
 area of tracking.
 Proximity method is known for its robustness because of its ability handle
 some interference cause by the environment, and also because of its low
 cost setup.
 Despite of that, the method is only able to detect the vicinity of a target
 and not the exact location itself thus decreasing its accuracy.
 It is also not easy to arrange, since sensors should be positioned correctly
 or confusion regarding the location of a target can happen.
 It is usually used in small areas or indoor setups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, scene analysis method studies the area of tracking to
 gather the signal strength of the target from a fixed sensor node with
 a given location.
 The signal strength would be tabulated along with its corresponding position
 to a database 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

.
 After the analysis and installation, tracking would start and sensors would
 compare the acquired signal strength of the target to the ones stored inside
 the database.
 Even if there is a database, sensors would still need to estimate the location
 since not all signal strengths can be mapped to a particular position on
 the area.
 Scene analysis method usually provides an accurate position but at the
 expense of time of analysis.
 If there is a large area of tracking, especially in an outdoor environment,
 it would definitely take time to gather the signal strength at multiple
 positions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last method is triangulation, which needs at least three base stations
 with known coordinates.
 These base stations are essential in locating a target since the acquired
 signal strengths per base station would be used to calculate the distance
 between the station and the target.
 Using the stations as centers and the calculated distance to the target
 as radii for each circle, the three circles would intersect at a common
 point which would provide the location of the target.
 Sometimes the location is not accurate because of signal strength discrepancies
 so other methods were developed with triangulation as their basis.
 These are Coverage Area Based Algorithm and Ring Overlapping Localization
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "4794164"

\end_inset

.
 This method is ideal for outdoor tracking since base stations are capable
 of a large coverage area but targets require a high amount of energy for
 transmitting data.
 The transceivers of the target would likely need an immediate access to
 charging in this method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tracking Devices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are multiple devices applicable for tracking not only on wireless
 mesh networks but in general.
 Examples are transceivers, RFIDs, and GPS
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "6583484"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "4492568"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "878533"

\end_inset

.
 The latter two are usually the main device used for tracking and for personal
 use.
 Though they are accessible, GPS and RFID require stable power sources which
 would limit the productivity of the bikes.
 Some transceivers are also accessible with different prices and signal
 ranges.
 Some of these transceivers are RF100, MICAz motes, Radiometrix RPC418,
 and MIT's Cricket.
 The following were tested on an indoor environment because of its signal
 range limitation.
 There are other transceivers that are less documented but also suited for
 tracking in WMN.
 These are CC430F and CC1101, which are capable of reaching distance from
 500 meters to 2 kilometers.
 Other valuable specification can be seen in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Comparison-of-Multiple-Transceiver"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From comparison CC430F is probably the best choice for a transceiver to
 be used by the node, despite of it having a higher current consumption
 compared to the others.
 Its range is a big factor and also because it can be powered by two AA
 batteries.
 The range of possible frequency of operation for the CC430F is between
 300 MHz to 928 MHz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "3"

\end_inset

.
 433 MHz would be the optimal frequency band since it is an unlicensed band
 and it is low enough such that its signal is able to pass through walls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a device called Wizzimote which has an embedded CC430F transceiver
 with a MSP430 microcontroller it is shown in Figure 2.2.
 It also has an open source protocol stack called DASH7 capable of multihopping
 and collision avoidance properties.
\end_layout

