\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DASH7 technology is designed as a OSI 7 layer, and it is seen as an improvement
 for the ISO/IEC 18000-7 protocol.
 One of the main differences between the two technologies are their MAC
 transmission protocol.
 DASH7 uses Carrirer Sense Multiple Access/Collision Avoidance while ISO/IEC
 18000-7 uses Slotted Aloha.
 The latter transmission is more prone to packet collision than the CSMA/CA
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "6831994"

\end_inset

.
 Collision of packets lead to delays in the network and for tracking system
 delays should be minimized as much as possible since target should be monitored
 carefully.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another difference between DASH7 and ISO/IEC 18000-7 is their utilization
 of channels.
 DASH7 can achieve a maximum of 8 channels while ISO/IEC 18000-7 has only
 one
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "6831994"

\end_inset

.
 With multiple channels, DASH7 would be able to lessen the collisions in
 a network.
 There are more difference between DASH7 and ISO/IEC 180000-7 shown on Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Physical-Layer-and"

\end_inset


\end_layout

