\begin_layout Chapter
Problem Statement and Objectives 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cha:ProbStatement"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous chapter we have tackled the different algorithms that are
 being used to determine the location of a unit inside a wireless mesh network.
 In this chapter we would be dictating our problem statement and the our
 objectives of our project
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently UP Bike Share intends to execute everything manually, i.e., rider
 registration, bike monitoring and quality control.
 In doing so they may not be able to check whether every rider is adhering
 to the rules that they have lain down, therefore there is no assurance
 that every bike is being used exclusively inside campus premises.
 There have been reports of bike sightings outside the vicinity of UP Diliman,
 e.g., Katipunan, Maginhawa, etc.
 They have also lost a few bikes since they have started, and this scenario
 can go on if no device is made to support their cause and strictly implement
 their rules.
 By creating a tech that could support their advocacy by tracking every
 bike in their arsenal, they would be able to track down the violators and
 give them a proper sanction, while ensuring that every bike and rider is
 kept safe and unharmed, leading towards a better biking community for UP
 Diliman.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Objectives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We intend to create an automated consolidating unit using a wireless mesh
 network that could monitor the whereabouts of the bike and the information
 of the rider that currently rented the bike.
 The bike share initiative intends to expand as the years progress, therefore
 that would mean more bikes, consequently more devices, since each bike
 would need its own tech, this is why the materials to be used to fabricate
 the device should be cheap.
 There is an initial plan that the tech could be powered by the pedaling
 motion of the biker, this can only be done if the device isn’t too power
 hungry.
 Riders wouldn’t like the idea of exerting too much effort in biking and
 keeping the device powered, that is why the device must need only a small
 amount of energy to power it.
 The device should have a way to monitor the whereabouts of the bikes accurately
 so that the location of each bike can be retrieved if or when needed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage cleardoublepage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Methodology
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cha:Methodology"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section discusses the methods and techniques that will be used to implement
 the project.
 This includes not only the actual implementation, but also how tests are
 designed and their results obtained and analyzed.
 The methodology may, if applicable, contain the following subsections:
 design, implementation, and testing.
 Alternative ways of organizing this section (that is more suited to the
 type of project being proposed) may be used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information on how the design will be obtained shall be presented.
 It shall be indicated whether the tools, parts, and algorithms that will
 be used in the project will be created by the author or taken from a different
 source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information on how the design will be implemented shall be presented.
 It shall be indicated if the labor is to be performed by the author or
 by a different source.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information on how the design and the implementation will be tested shall
 be presented.
 Moreover, information on how the test results will be evaluated against
 the specifications or goals of the project shall also be stated.
